Your intuition that mathematics/simulation and reality might share the same “plane” is actually a question philosophers and scientists have argued about for a long time. There are a few main ways people interpret that feeling.

⸻

1. The “Same Plane” Idea (Mathematical Realism)

Some physicists and philosophers think mathematical structures exist independently of us.

This view is often called mathematical Platonism.

The idea is:

mathematical structure
      ↓
physical universe instantiates that structure

Under that view:
	•	mathematics isn’t invented
	•	it’s discovered
	•	physical laws are expressions of deeper mathematical patterns

A well-known advocate of this idea is Max Tegmark, who proposed the Mathematical Universe Hypothesis.

In that view, simulations sometimes “predict reality” because both are exploring the same mathematical landscape.

⸻

2. The “Tool for Compression” Idea

Another view is that mathematics works so well because it’s an extremely good language for compressing patterns.

Reality has regularities:
	•	gravity behaves consistently
	•	atoms follow predictable rules
	•	waves propagate mathematically

Mathematics captures those regularities efficiently.

So when a theory predicts something new, it’s often because the math faithfully captured an existing pattern.

Example discoveries predicted by math first:

Discovery	Predicted by math
Neptune	orbital equations
Antimatter	Dirac equation
Gravitational waves	Einstein’s equations

In this view math and reality aren’t literally the same plane — math is just an extremely powerful modeling tool.

⸻

3. The “Structure Emergence” View

Another interpretation is that structure emerges naturally from physical laws, and mathematics is the study of structure itself.

So when we build mathematical models, we are effectively exploring:

possible structures

Reality is one of those structures.

Simulations can sometimes reach new discoveries because they explore neighboring structures near the real one.

⸻

4. Why Simulations Can Discover Things

When simulations are built from accurate rules, they can explore combinations humans haven’t thought about yet.

Example process:

known physical laws
↓
mathematical model
↓
simulation explores parameter space
↓
unexpected behavior appears
↓
scientists test if it exists in reality

That’s why simulations sometimes find new phenomena.

⸻

5. Your “Perception Band” Idea Fits Here

Humans directly perceive only a small slice of reality.

Mathematics and simulation act like cognitive instruments, extending perception into areas we cannot observe directly.

For example:
	•	black holes were predicted mathematically before observation
	•	gravitational waves were predicted a century before detection

Simulation and mathematics let us explore possible structures beyond immediate observation.

⸻

6. The Knight Move Again

This ties back to your chess metaphor.

The process often looks like:

observation
↓
mathematical abstraction
↓
exploration of possibilities
↓
return to reality for testing

So the “knight move” is leaving the observed world briefly, exploring the mathematical space, and then coming back with predictions.

⸻

7. What We Actually Know

Right now science doesn’t have a definitive answer about whether:
	•	mathematics is discovered
	•	mathematics is invented
	•	or reality is fundamentally mathematical

All three ideas have supporters.

But what is clear is that mathematics and simulation are extremely effective ways to extend human understanding beyond our perception band.

